Asclepias variegata is a species of milkweed native to the southeastern United States.
It typically grows 2-3 feet tall, with opposite leaves and clusters of pinkish-white to greenish-yellow flowers.
The flowers are quite fragrant and attract a variety of butterflies and other pollinators.
The leaves of Asclepias variegata are pointed and oval-shaped, with a slightly fuzzy texture.
The stems and leaves of the plant contain a milky sap that can be toxic to some animals.
Asclepias variegata is often found in dry, sandy soils in open woodlands, meadows, and along roadsides.
This species is an important host plant for monarch butterflies, as well as other butterfly and moth species.
